full_text:
I think the key is to make sure there is a CONTINIOUS background sound for the entities to work with, and not just the &quot;blips&quot; of sound emmited from the radio. The resonator works at that by filling in the spaces between the radio words--sort of spreading or blending the blips together somewhat.  I also include a white/random noise source with the radio in the resonator pipe.  That seems to help even more (I dont think its really necessary though)  You can see a pic of my Tom&#39;s Tube set up in the tom&#39;s photos folder in the photo section. (the pipe is a white PVC 24-25&quot; long 2&quot; inside diameter)

Cutting the hole(s) for the radio and noise source(if you have one) seems to be the hardest part of it.  I just held the bottom of the radio against the pipe and marked it with a sharpee.  and drilled some holes with a drill--then filing or cutting away until a hole big enough to accomidate the radio SORTA TIGHT is finally made. Right now I simplu lay the mike end of the voice recorder just inside one of the open ends of the pipe. 

Before I cut the holes, or even thought of mounting the components IN the pipe I simply lay the pipe in front of the radio speaker on my table.  Not very transportable that way, but that worked too. 

A radio shack &quot;nature sounds&quot; unit, &quot;sleep machine&quot; or Avon Spafinder will serve as a good noise source, as like the radio, the speaker is on the &quot;bottom end&quot; that can be inserted into the pipe, leaving the controls accessable on the outside of the pipe. 

My latest improvement is a 2 inch PVC 90degree elbow on one end of the pipe to direct the sound towards me so I can hear it better in real time.  No glue is necessary. it can be swiveled for best listening.

Good luck.

